TY  - JOUR
AU  - Armstrong, Mark
T1  - Price Discrimination by a Many-Product Firm
PY  - 1999
Y1  - 1999/01/01
DO  - 10.1111/1467-937X.00082
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 66
IS  - 1
SP  - 151
EP  - 168
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - Determining the optimal selling strategy for a multiproduct firm facing consumers with unobservable tastes is a difficult task. This paper aims to show how almost optimal nonlinear tariffs can often be found when the number of products is large. Moreover, such tariffs take a simple form: (i) when taste parameters are independently distributed across products, the almost optimal tariff is a single cost-based two-part tariff which can extract virtually all consumer surplus; (ii) when tastes are correlated across products, perhaps because of income differences across consumers, the almost optimal tariff can be implemented as a menu of two-part tariffs each of which has prices proportional to marginal costs.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1467-937X.00082
ER  - 



